const a=[{id:1,companion:"Abu Bakr al-Siddiq",companionAr:"أبو بكر الصديق",companionRank:1,laqab:"Al-Siddiq",laqabAr:"الصِّدِّيق",laqabEn:"The Exceptionally Truthful / The Confirmer of Truth",occasionEn:"Given after Abu Bakr unhesitatingly believed the Prophet's account of the Night Journey (Isra' and Mi'raj) when all of Mecca scoffed and demanded he retract his belief in it.",prophetsWordsAr:"صَدَّقَهُ أَبُو بَكْرٍ. فَسُمِّيَ الصِّدِّيقَ",prophetsWordsEn:'Abu Bakr confirmed it (as true) — and he was thereby named "al-Siddiq."',source:"Tabarani in Al-Kabir 7638; Ibn Ishaq in Seerah; Hakim in Al-Mustadrak 4398",significance:"Al-Siddiq is the highest form of the word sidq (truth). It means one who is perpetually, instinctively truthful — and who confirms truth even when all others deny it. This was the Prophet's personal label for his dearest friend. Abu Bakr remains the only companion whose Quranic appellation (4:69) places him among the rank of the Siddiqeen (the Truthful Ones) alongside prophets and martyrs.",color:"#b8860b"},{id:2,companion:"Umar ibn al-Khattab",companionAr:"عمر بن الخطاب",companionRank:2,laqab:"Al-Faruq",laqabAr:"الفَارُوق",laqabEn:"The Distinguisher Between Truth and Falsehood",occasionEn:"Given on the occasion of Umar's public declaration of his Islam in Mecca — the first companion to openly announce his faith in broad daylight, marching to the Ka'ba despite all threats. Some narrations add it was revealed via Jibreel (Gabriel) himself.",prophetsWordsAr:"اللَّهُمَّ أَعِزَّ الإِسْلَامَ بِعُمَرَ بْنِ الخَطَّابِ. فَسُمِّيَ الفَارُوقَ لِأَنَّهُ فَرَّقَ بَيْنَ الحَقِّ وَالبَاطِلِ",prophetsWordsEn:"O Allah, strengthen Islam by Umar ibn al-Khattab. And he was called al-Faruq because he distinguished between truth and falsehood.",source:"Tirmidhi 3681; Ibn Majah 104; Musnad Ahmad 385",significance:`Faruq derives from faraqa — to split, separate, distinguish. The nickname acknowledged Umar's extraordinary clarity of judgement, his inability to tolerate ambiguity in matters of right and wrong. Numerous Quranic ayahs were revealed aligning with Umar's previously stated opinions (muwafaqat Umar). He is the only companion of whom the Prophet ﷺ said: "Truth speaks on the tongue of Umar."`,color:"#1a3462"},{id:3,companion:"Uthman ibn Affan",companionAr:"عثمان بن عفان",companionRank:3,laqab:"Dhul-Nurayn",laqabAr:"ذُو النُّورَيْن",laqabEn:"Possessor of the Two Lights",occasionEn:"Given because Uthman married two daughters of the Prophet ﷺ sequentially — first Ruqayya, and after her death, Umm Kulthum. He is the only man in history known to have married two daughters of a prophet.",prophetsWordsAr:"مَا رَأَيْتُ أَحَداً أَشْبَهَ صَلَاةً وَلَا حِلْماً بِرَسُولِ اللَّهِ مِنْ عُثْمَانَ",prophetsWordsEn:"I have not seen anyone whose prayer and forbearance resembles the Messenger of Allah ﷺ more than Uthman.",source:"Tabarani in Al-Awsat; Ibn Asakir in Tarikh Dimashq 39/3; Kanz al-Ummal",significance:`The "two lights" (nurayn) refer to his two wives — daughters of the Prophet ﷺ — both of whom were described in their own time as lights of beauty and piety. This nickname elevated Uthman's familial bond to the Prophet ﷺ above all other companions. When Ruqayya died on the day of Badr, the Prophet ﷺ gave him Umm Kulthum, reportedly saying: "If I had a third, I would have given her too." When Umm Kulthum also died, the Prophet ﷺ openly wept.`,color:"#8b4513"},{id:4,companion:"Ali ibn Abi Talib",companionAr:"علي بن أبي طالب",companionRank:4,laqab:"Asadullah al-Ghalib",laqabAr:"أَسَدُ اللَّهِ الغَالِب",laqabEn:"The Prevailing Lion of Allah",occasionEn:"Given during single combat at various battles, most prominently referenced after the Battle of Khaybar (7 AH) when Ali carried a gate as a shield and defeated the champion Marhab.",prophetsWordsAr:"لَأُعْطِيَنَّ الرَّايَةَ غَداً رَجُلاً يُحِبُّ اللَّهَ وَرَسُولَهُ وَيُحِبُّهُ اللَّهُ وَرَسُولُهُ",prophetsWordsEn:"I will surely give the banner tomorrow to a man who loves Allah and His Messenger and whom Allah and His Messenger love.",source:"Bukhari 2975; Muslim 2407; Musnad Ahmad 3061",significance:'Ali is the only companion called both "Lion of Allah" (Asadullah) and "Hand of Allah" (Yadullah) in Islamic tradition. His physical courage — fighting in 100 battles by some accounts — was matched by his spiritual rank. The Prophet ﷺ famously said at Khaybar that the flag would go to "one who loves Allah and His Messenger." The entire camp hoped for it. It went to Ali. He also holds the additional laqab "Abu Turab" (Father of Dust) — the nickname the Prophet ﷺ gave him most affectionately after finding him asleep on the ground.',color:"#0a4030"},{id:5,companion:"Hamza ibn Abd al-Muttalib",companionAr:"حمزة بن عبد المطلب",companionRank:7,laqab:"Sayyid al-Shuhada",laqabAr:"سَيِّد الشُّهَدَاء",laqabEn:"Master / Chief of the Martyrs",occasionEn:"Bestowed posthumously by the Prophet ﷺ after Hamza was martyred and mutilated at the Battle of Uhud (3 AH/625 CE), where his liver was extracted and chewed by Hind bint Utba.",prophetsWordsAr:"حَمْزَةُ سَيِّدُ الشُّهَدَاءِ",prophetsWordsEn:"Hamza is the master of the martyrs.",source:"Hakim in Al-Mustadrak 4880; Tabarani in Al-Kabir 2952; Ibn Abi Shayba 37982",significance:`The Prophet ﷺ stood over Hamza's mutilated body at Uhud and wept such that his shoulders shook. He swore an oath of retaliation then — so powerful was his grief — but Allah revealed 16:126–127 tempering him toward patience. Hamza was buried alongside his nephew Abdullah ibn Jahsh under a single shroud because there was not enough cloth for both. He was additionally named "Asadullah wa Asad Rasulillah" (Lion of Allah and Lion of His Messenger) — the only companion to receive two Asad titles.`,color:"#8b1a38"},{id:6,companion:"Khalid ibn al-Walid",companionAr:"خالد بن الوليد",companionRank:14,laqab:"Saifullah al-Maslul",laqabAr:"سَيْفُ اللَّهِ المَسْلُول",laqabEn:"The Drawn Sword of Allah",occasionEn:"Given by the Prophet ﷺ after the Battle of Mu'ta (8 AH) in which Khalid — not even the appointed commander — assumed leadership after all three designated commanders (Zayd ibn Haritha, Ja'far ibn Abi Talib, and Abdullah ibn Rawaha) were killed, and extricated the Muslim army from certain annihilation against a Roman force of 200,000.",prophetsWordsAr:"خَالِدٌ سَيْفٌ مِنْ سُيُوفِ اللَّهِ سَلَّهُ اللَّهُ عَلَى الكَافِرِين",prophetsWordsEn:"Khalid is a sword from among the swords of Allah which He has drawn against the disbelievers.",source:"Bukhari 4262; Tabarani in Al-Kabir 3832; Seerah Ibn Hisham (Battle of Mu'ta)",significance:`Khalid had been the fiercest enemy of Islam, commanding the Meccan cavalry at Badr and Uhud and nearly defeating the Muslims at Uhud. His conversion (8 AH) shocked the Muslim world. He then led conquest after conquest — Mu'ta, Mecca, Hunayn, Yamama (crushing the Ridda Wars), and the entire Persian/Roman campaign in Syria and Iraq. He reportedly said on his deathbed: "I have fought in so many battles seeking martyrdom, yet I die in my bed like a camel. Let the cowards' eyes never rest." He died in 21 AH in Homs, Syria.`,color:"#6b3d0a"},{id:7,companion:"Abu Ubayda ibn al-Jarrah",companionAr:"أبو عبيدة بن الجراح",companionRank:9,laqab:"Amin al-Ummah",laqabAr:"أَمِين الأُمَّة",laqabEn:"Trustee / The Trustworthy One of the Nation",occasionEn:'Declared by the Prophet ﷺ in a famous hadith listing the unique qualities of different companions: "Every nation has its trustee, and the trustee of this nation is Abu Ubayda ibn al-Jarrah."',prophetsWordsAr:"لِكُلِّ أُمَّةٍ أَمِينٌ، وَأَمِينُ هَذِهِ الأُمَّةِ أَبُو عُبَيْدَةَ بْنُ الجَرَّاحِ",prophetsWordsEn:"Every nation has its trustee, and the trustee of this nation is Abu Ubayda ibn al-Jarrah.",source:"Bukhari 3744; Muslim 2419; Tirmidhi 3792",significance:"Abu Ubayda exemplified unimpeachable integrity. He was so trustworthy that when the dying Abu Bakr wanted to name a successor, he first tried to name Abu Ubayda. At the decisive battle of Yarmouk, commanding one of the largest Muslim armies in history, he was also known for extraordinary humility: when 1,000 gold coins were sent to him as a gift, he distributed every dirham before morning. He was martyred by the plague of Amwas in 18 AH, 639 CE — refusing to flee from the stricken area.",color:"#2a5080"},{id:8,companion:"Bilal ibn Rabah",companionAr:"بلال بن رباح",companionRank:10,laqab:"Mu'azzin al-Jannah",laqabAr:"مُؤَذِّن الجَنَّة",laqabEn:"The Caller to Prayer of Paradise",occasionEn:"The Prophet ﷺ heard Bilal's footsteps in Paradise during the Isra' and Mi'raj, and informed him. Bilal became the first and most beloved muezzin in Islamic history — his voice was described as the most beautiful of voices by the Prophet ﷺ.",prophetsWordsAr:"إِنِّي سَمِعْتُ دَفَّ نَعْلَيْكَ بَيْنَ يَدَيَّ فِي الجَنَّةِ",prophetsWordsEn:"I heard the sound of your sandals before me in Paradise.",source:"Bukhari 1149; Muslim 2458; Tirmidhi 3689",significance:`Bilal was an Abyssinian slave tortured by his master Umayya ibn Khalaf for saying "Ahad, Ahad" (One, One — referring to Allah's oneness) under burning rocks and hot iron. Abu Bakr purchased and freed him. The Prophet ﷺ then made him the first official mu'azzin of Islam — a profound statement that the voice of Islam would be that of a formerly enslaved African man. After the Prophet's death, Bilal could not bear to give the adhan in Medina — his voice broke every time he reached "Ash-hadu anna Muhammadan rasulullah" and wept. He emigrated to Syria where he lived until death.`,color:"#4a3020"},{id:9,companion:"Zayd ibn Haritha",companionAr:"زيد بن حارثة",companionRank:16,laqab:"Hibb Rasulillah",laqabAr:"حِبُّ رَسُولِ اللَّهِ",laqabEn:"The Beloved of the Messenger of Allah",occasionEn:"Called so throughout his life by companions who knew the depth of the Prophet's love for him. When Zayd's father came to Mecca to take him home after finding him there as a slave, Zayd chose the Prophet ﷺ over his own family — a moment the Prophet ﷺ remembered always.",prophetsWordsAr:"مَا زَالَ الحِبُّ يُحِبُّنَا مُنْذُ عَرَفْنَا",prophetsWordsEn:"Al-Hibb (the beloved one) has loved us since we first knew each other.",source:"Tabarani in Al-Kabir; Ibn Asakir in Tarikh Dimashq; Seerah Ibn Hisham (Zayd's story)",significance:`Zayd ibn Haritha holds three unique distinctions: (1) He is the only companion named by personal name in the Quran (33:37 — "Zayd" — unprecedented and intentional). (2) He was appointed commander of the Mu'ta expedition ahead of senior companions. (3) His son Usama ibn Zayd was appointed commander of an army that included Abu Bakr and Umar — the Prophet ﷺ's ultimate statement about meritocracy over lineage. Zayd was martyred at Mu'ta in 8 AH/629 CE.`,color:"#5a3800"},{id:10,companion:"Sa'd ibn Abi Waqqas",companionAr:"سعد بن أبي وقاص",companionRank:8,laqab:"Asad al-Islam (and Sahib al-Du'a al-Mustajab)",laqabAr:"أَسَدُ الإِسْلَام / صَاحِبُ الدُّعَاء المُسْتَجَاب",laqabEn:"Lion of Islam / The One Whose Prayers Are Answered",occasionEn:`The Prophet ﷺ prayed for Sa'd ibn Abi Waqqas specifically: "O Allah, guide his arrow and answer his du'a." Sa'd became famously known as the companion whose every du'a was accepted — a fact that made even Umar cautious about angering him.`,prophetsWordsAr:"اللَّهُمَّ سَدِّدْ رَمْيَتَهُ وَأَجِبْ دَعْوَتَهُ",prophetsWordsEn:"O Allah, make his arrow accurate and answer his supplication.",source:"Tirmidhi 3752; Musnad Ahmad 1478; Tabarani in Al-Awsat",significance:`Sa'd was the first Muslim to shoot an arrow in the path of Allah (at the Battle of Waddan). He was one of the first six to accept Islam. The Prophet ﷺ famously said to him at Uhud: "Irmī, Sa'd! Fidāka abi wa ummi!" (Shoot, Sa'd! My father and mother be your ransom!) — the only time the Prophet ﷺ sacrificed both his parents for a companion simultaneously. As commander of al-Qadisiyya, he defeated the Sassanid Empire and brought Persia into the Islamic world.`,color:"#8b1a1a"},{id:11,companion:"Zayd ibn Thabit al-Ansari",companionAr:"زيد بن ثابت الأنصاري",companionRank:28,laqab:"Amin al-Quran",laqabAr:"أَمِين القُرآن",laqabEn:"Trustee of the Quran",occasionEn:"Given by consensus of the companions and affirmed by Abu Bakr and Umar, who entrusted Zayd with the compilation of the Quran — both after Abu Bakr's commission (after Yamama) and Uthman's standardisation commission.",prophetsWordsAr:"أَفْرَضُكُمْ زَيْدُ بْنُ ثَابِتٍ",prophetsWordsEn:"The most knowledgeable of you in matters of inheritance is Zayd ibn Thabit.",source:"Tirmidhi 2885; Bukhari 7396 (on Quran collection); Ibn Sa'd in Tabaqat",significance:"Zayd learned to write at the Prophet's direction, then learned Hebrew and Syriac within 15 days so he could read the letters of Jewish and Christian delegations to the Prophet ﷺ. He served as the Prophet's chief secretary. He is one of the primary architects of the Quran as we read it today — his Mushaf was the template used for Uthman's standardized copies sent to all provinces. Without Zayd, the textual preservation of the Quran may have been far more complex.",color:"#2a5080"},{id:12,companion:"Ammar ibn Yasir",companionAr:"عمار بن ياسر",companionRank:27,laqab:"Mala'a Allah Iman",laqabAr:"مَلَأَهُ اللَّهُ إِيمَاناً",laqabEn:"Whom Allah Has Filled With Faith",occasionEn:"A description rather than a formal title, given by the Prophet ﷺ when he saw Ammar being tortured mercilessly with his parents by the pagan Abu Jahl. The Prophet ﷺ could only pass by and whisper encouragement — it was the darkest hour of Islam.",prophetsWordsAr:"صَبْرًا آلَ يَاسِرٍ فَإِنَّ مَوْعِدَكُمُ الجَنَّةُ",prophetsWordsEn:"Be patient, O family of Yasir! Your appointment is with Paradise.",source:"Hakim in Al-Mustadrak 5659; Ibn Ishaq in Seerah; Tabarani in Al-Kabir",significance:`Ammar's mother Sumayyah was the first martyr in Islam — killed by Abu Jahl with a spear. His father Yasir died under torture the same day. Ammar himself was forced to utter words of disbelief to avoid death — a moment for which the Quran descended with special relief (16:106). He was later described by the Prophet ﷺ as one who is skinned to the bone in his love for truth. He was martyred at the Battle of Siffin (37 AH/657 CE) at over 90 years old — a death the Prophet ﷺ had prophesied decades earlier: "The transgressing party will kill Ammar."`,color:"#7a2060"},{id:13,companion:"Anas ibn Malik",companionAr:"أنس بن مالك",companionRank:19,laqab:"Khadim Rasulillah",laqabAr:"خَادِمُ رَسُولِ اللَّهِ",laqabEn:"Servant of the Messenger of Allah",occasionEn:`His mother Umm Sulaym brought the ten-year-old Anas to the Prophet ﷺ in Medina saying: "O Messenger of Allah, here is my son Anas who will serve you." Anas remained in the Prophet's service for a full ten years — through all the battles, the revelations, the joys, and the grief.`,prophetsWordsAr:"اللَّهُمَّ أَكْثِرْ مَالَهُ وَوَلَدَهُ وَبَارِكْ لَهُ فِيمَا أَعْطَيْتَهُ",prophetsWordsEn:"O Allah, increase his wealth and his children, and bless him in what You have given him.",source:"Bukhari 6334; Muslim 660; Tirmidhi 3828",significance:`Anas ibn Malik lived to approximately 103 years old, transmitting over 2,286 hadith — one of the highest narration counts of any companion. He said: "The Prophet ﷺ served in my home for ten years. He never once said 'Ugh' (an expression of displeasure) to anything I did, never asked why I did something I did, never asked why I didn't do something I didn't do." The Prophet ﷺ's du'a for Anas was answered: Anas reportedly had 80+ children and grandchildren, and his garden in Basra yielded fruit twice a year.`,color:"#0a5e3f"},{id:14,companion:"Abdullah ibn Masud",companionAr:"عبد الله بن مسعود",companionRank:22,laqab:"Sahib al-Siwakin (and Tarjuman al-Quran)",laqabAr:"صَاحِبُ السِّوَاكَيْن / تَرْجُمَانُ القُرآن",laqabEn:"The Keeper of the Two Sticks (and Interpreter of the Quran)",occasionEn:`Abdullah ibn Masud carried the Prophet's miswak (toothstick) and sandals — a mark of intimate personal service. The playful nickname "keeper of the two sticks" referred to his permanent carry of the sandals and miswak. He was also called "Sahib al-Wisada" (Keeper of the Pillow/Cushion). His Quranic nickname reflects his status as the foremost Quran interpreter.`,prophetsWordsAr:"مَنْ أَحَبَّ أَنْ يَقْرَأَ القُرآنَ غَضًّا كَمَا أُنْزِلَ فَلْيَقْرَأْهُ بِقِرَاءَةِ ابْنِ أُمِّ عَبْدٍ",prophetsWordsEn:"Whoever wishes to recite the Quran fresh as it was revealed, let him recite it with the recitation of Ibn Umm Abd (Ibn Masud).",source:"Ibn Majah 138; Musnad Ahmad 3593; Tafsir Ibn Kathir Introduction",significance:`Ibn Masud learned 70 surahs directly from the Prophet ﷺ's mouth. He was the first to recite Quran publicly in Mecca — beaten savagely for it and returning the next day to do it again. Umar said: "Let the one who loves to know the recitation of the Quran as it was revealed go to Ibn Masud." He was so learned that Ali ibn Abi Talib said: "I would not put anyone above Ibn Masud for knowledge of the Quran." Yet he was also described as thin-legged and short — "smaller than others in body, greater than them in all else."`,color:"#7a5a00"},{id:15,companion:"Salman al-Farisi",companionAr:"سلمان الفارسي",companionRank:29,laqab:"Salman al-Khayr",laqabAr:"سَلْمَان الخَيْر",laqabEn:"Salman of Goodness / Salman the Good",occasionEn:`A title reflecting his extraordinary life's journey and his embodiment of pure spiritual seeking. The Prophet ﷺ also famously declared: "Salman is one of the People of my House" — an extraordinary inclusion of a Persian convert into the Prophet's family.`,prophetsWordsAr:"سَلْمَانُ مِنَّا أَهْلَ البَيْت",prophetsWordsEn:"Salman is from us — the People of the Household.",source:"Hakim in Al-Mustadrak 6541; Tabarani in Al-Kabir; Ibn Asakir in Tarikh Dimashq",significance:`Salman's life story is one of the most remarkable in Islamic history: born Zoroastrian in Persia, he left home seeking truth, became a Christian monk in Syria, served various priests through Syria, Mosul, Amuriyya — each dying and directing him to "a prophet who will arise in Arabia" — until he came to Medina, met the Prophet ﷺ, and identified him by the seal of prophethood. It was his idea to dig the Trench (Khandaq) at the Battle of the Trench — a tactic unknown to Arabs — which saved Medina. He later became governor of al-Mada'in (Ctesiphon) but lived as ascetically as any dervish.`,color:"#4a5800"}];export{a as L};
